  <h2 id="what-are-sinks">What are Sinks?</h2>

  <p>
    Sinks are output destinations for generated data. Instead of just printing to stdout, you can
    send data directly to databases, files, or other systems.
  </p>

  <h2 id="available-sinks">Available Sinks</h2>

  <h3>MySQL Sink</h3>

  <p>Write data directly to MySQL databases.</p>

  <pre><code>datagenc gen users.dg --sink mysql --count 1000</code></pre>

  <p>
    See <a href="/odin/docs/sinks/mysql">MySQL Sink Configuration</a> for details.
  </p>

  <h3>Stdout Sink</h3>

  <p>Default sink that writes to standard output.</p>

  <pre><code>datagenc gen users.dg --count 100</code></pre>

  <h3>File Sink</h3>

  <p>Write to files in various formats (JSON, CSV, SQL).</p>

  <pre><code>datagenc gen users.dg --output users.json --count 1000</code></pre>

  <h2>Sink Configuration</h2>

  <p>
    Each sink has its own configuration options. See individual sink documentation for specific
    parameters.
  </p>

